node.text:
Filmed in 2018. The hippopotamus is one of the most dangerous animals in Africa. I had full confidence in my guide and his safety instructions, but there were a few nervous moments.

Running away from a hippo with a camera and reasonably sized lens is not a comfortable experience, as turning around to check whether the charge is a mock one, is not natural. Instinctively, the reaction to a charge is to run.

99.9% of the time the hippo is bluffing, but those moments are never about doing the maths.⁣⁣⁣

#Hippopotamus #Hippo #Zambezi #Photography

node.text:
Tasmanian Devils are making a comeback. Friends of @wild.ark, @ChrisHemsworth and @elsapatakyconfidentia, helped release 11 Tasmanian Devils to the wild on September 10. They are among the first Tasmanian Devils to live in the wild on mainland Australia in 3,000 years.
⁣⁣⁣⁣
The team at @AussieArk will monitor the marsupials in the 400-hectare wildlife sanctuary through camera traps, radio collars and surveys to check on how the marsupials are adjusting to life in the wild. So far, the Tasmanian Devils are making a #DevilComeback! ⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
Support them on their journey on the @wild.ark account. ⁣⁣⁣⁣

node.text:
It seems a long time since I visited Australia to witness the devastation of the wildfires and the world has obviously changed dramatically since then. It is a difficult time to navigate the world of charitable endeavour as everything now seems dwarfed by the threat we currently face. This piece of news from the field still served as a heart-warming message to me when I received it last week. I hope it carries the same weight for all of those who helped deliver it. Thank you.⁣
⁣
3 months ago when I arrived in Australia I was greeted by a scene from an apocalypse film – with destruction on a scale I hadn’t seen before. Shaken, I was compelled to launch the The #KoalaComeback Campaign alongside @wild.ark and @global_wildlife_conservation to try and give back.⁣
⁣
The support for the campaign was inspiring, quickly raising over $1.4 million. The money raised is already being deployed on the ground with the latest grant of $30,000 going to the @currumbinwildlifehospital to support their life-saving work in the aftermath of the bushfires.⁣
⁣
In these uncertain times, some positive news could not be more welcomed and I want to thank everybody who supported and gave generously to this important cause. And a special thanks to @genesis_imaging and Ken Sethi, for printing all of the images free of charge. We couldn’t do what we do without you.⁣
⁣
I hope money from our campaign can continue to fund grants like this to many more organisations in the coming months – these organisations will need it now more than ever.

We are thrilled that over $1.1 million has been raised so far for @wild.ark and @global_wildlife_conservation through The #KoalaComeback Campaign thanks to partners, friends and collaborators getting behind the effort as well as generous contributions coming in from the public. The messages of support from all over the world have been inspiring so thank you.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
The initial target of $2 million is within reaching distance. Please, if you have not donated and would like to support the campaign, visit the link in my bio or go to www.koalacomeback.com to claim your own print by me.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
A special thanks to @genesis_imaging and Ken Sethi, who will be doing all of the printing of images for no charge. If any serious photographer in London does not use Genesis for their printing and framing, they should now. They are manifestly a class apart on every level.

We are proud to launch Volume Three of In Focus. 

When we work in captivating locations with exceptionally talented people from divergent trades, there will always be stories to tell. 

We are delighted to share with you our stories from the past six months. 

The September Issue of In Focus includes DYP’s recent work with GRAMMY Award-winning singer-songwriter Ciara and NFL quarterback Russell Wilson, the American activist, businesswoman, model and DJ, Paris Hilton and a behind the scenes look at our photographic anthology to the American Wild West featuring supermodel Cara Delevingne.

Will Bolsover, CEO of Natural World Safaris, discusses the impact of COVID-19 on wildlife travel; Charlie Mayhew, Founder and CEO of Tusk, talks about the 2021 Tusk Lion Trail and David chats with American wildlife artist John Banovich.

We would like to thank each of our collaborators and partners who are integral to the production of In Focus. Buy now by clicking on the shopping link in the video or head to the link in our bio.

Distributing now.

node.text:
Bearish

Bears are not an easy subject matter for me; in part because the backdrops are often a little messy, and in part the obvious safety issues. Fortunately, bears in Katmai, Alaska during the summer salmon runs are used to sharing rivers with fishermen and are largely comfortable with human presence. 

The biggest issue for me, however, is that my default position is to try and glorify an animal and that tends to draw me towards the biggest versions of a species. With bears, that is being a little greedy, and in Katmai, one simply has to work with what is available.

Last week, however, this beautiful and sizeable sow caught our eye and one rainy morning she put on a little show for us out in the tundra. The light was marginal, but I just about got away with it. I was always looking for the head on shot and the rain added another layer of textural detail to what is a stunning bear. 

This was the only photograph I took away from five long days in the field, but that’s fine with me. As with the fishermen up in Katmai; it is not the number of fish you catch, but the size of the biggest one. 

I want to thank our excellent pilots Chad and Devon for looking after us so well in and out of Iliamna.

We are humbled to partake in the 2021 Tusk Lion Trail, an international art installation in support of African conservation. The trail comprises 47 life-sized lion sculptures, which will be on display in iconic locations around the globe. With the first sculpture being unveiled this morning in Wellington, New Zealand, by rugby All-Black great Richie McCaw.

The patchwork of photographs of lions on both sculptures is testimony to our partners on the ground in East Africa and South Africa. In particular, I would acknowledge that my partnership with Kevin Richardson - The Lion Whisperer - has helped me enormously over the years. There is no greater friend of the lion in Africa and I am delighted that his name will be on one of the art works. Tusk and Kevin are best in class operators, and I am humbled to be affiliated to both parties.

The physical production of the lions would not have been possible without the help of my close friend Ken Sethi and his team at Genesis Imaging. They have helped with a number of charitable projects over the past few years but wrapping a sculpture of a lion was a new challenge; one they rose to in a fashion typical of their “can do” attitude. We’d also like to thank artist Eliot Haigh for painting the lions.

Today the global trail will be unveiled with DYP’s lions on display in St James’s Quarter in Edinburgh and The Royal Exchange in London.

#WorldLionDay #TuskLionTrail

Professional photography should not be competitive - it should be collegiate and every day we see pictures of others that we love. We celebrate the photographer and are reminded why we are so passionate about the craft. Sports photography was where I started so of course it remains a genre that I keep a close eye on - especially during the Olympics.

So today we raise our glasses to Donald Miralle (@donaldmiralle) - what a sensational image from Tokyo. It has everything.

I am excited to be speaking tonight at the famous Shinnecock Hills Golf Club in Southampton, Long Island. I look forward to seeing old friends and a few stars from sports, fashion and film. Flattered to hear it’s oversold - there can’t be much else going on.

I am a poor golfer, but I was accorded one big privilege in that world when I was asked by Augusta Golf Club to take this image back in 2016 - The Mount Rushmore of Golf. It was sadly one of the last official pictures of the legendary Arnold Palmer before he passed later that year.

I remember being a touch nervous when handed that responsibility - nervous and of course humbled by what was in front of my lens.

The Jungle Book Stories for #GlobalTigerDay

There were only about 1,700 Royal Bengal Tigers left in India at the time this photograph was taken in 2013 – a frightening decline from the estimated 100,000 during the Raj. Therefore, to find a father and son bathing in the same pool in the jungle was statistically unlikely. 

The positioning of the animals relative to the surroundings or each other is a matter of luck. Over time, luck will average out, but the placement of the adult tiger’s left ear covering his son’s right eye enhances a picture which evokes jungle book stories. 

I like the lone eye to the right – even though it’s outside my focal plane, it ironically grabs our focused eyes.

node.text:
The End of the Line⁣
⁣
Longhorn cattle are not only emblematic of Texas, they are also surely some of the most visually spectacular cows in the world. On location on the abandoned film set of “There Will Be Blood”, we tried different combinations with a few prize-winning cows.
⁣
This composition was a test of the crew’s patience and all my thanks go to Ryon Marshall and his fellow cowboys, who worked with great skill. Working Texas cowboys are the real deal - they work their cattle everyday.  From an art perspective I sensed that the bull should be facing me and there were no tension points with his horns.
⁣
Rail roads were so integral to the great push West as indeed were wagons and it struck me that they could complement each other outside a station. There is no real need for people to be in the image - there is enough there and the composition works. Rail tracks are great props for artists - they offer a whiff of romanticism and they also lead the eye.

node.text:
LFG

This has not been an easy 15 months for filmmakers and photographers - with travel restrictions, cancelled events and movie theatres and galleries closed.

The denouement of COVID is also proving to be painstakingly slow. We all may not be where we wanted to be this autumn.

But I do fancy that those who earn their living behind a lens are ready to give their all in the months ahead and this will start right now with photographers in Tokyo for the Olympics.

There is a great deal of pent up creative energy ready to be unleashed. I have huge respect for the seasoned photographers covering the Olympics having been a very average one myself way back at Calgary in 1988. It’s not easy to be different.

For our part, we are excited for the months ahead and will do all we can to make up for lost time. I look forward to the many confirmed shows we have in the second half of the year in places such as Monaco, London, Oslo, Dallas, Chicago, Nantucket, Connecticut, Santa Fe, Antwerp, Zurich and Paris. In between that, we will be filming in Antarctica, Alaska, California and South Africa. Then, of course all, roads lead to Art Miami. It’s going to be busy.

We start our shows next week in the Hamptons and I look forward to seeing many old friends. Time to get back into the saddle.

On location, Shibu Onsen

Taking the photograph Grumpy Monkey

The timeless Japanese village of Shibu Onsen is a microcosm of quintessential rural Japan. It was a perfect base from which to hike up and photograph the iconic snow monkeys that can be found in the region.

This picture, on a bleak and cold winter’s day, probably works because everything about it is miserable to the point of being comical. The misty and dank weather matches the Snow Monkey’s mood. I had no light to play with and this is technically reflected in the lack of depth of focus.

Wishing Tokyo the best possible Olympics in tough circumstances.

Blade Runner

In 2017, I spent eight days in North Korea. Given the escalation of tension between the reclusive country and America, my timing for this long arranged trip was luckily about as good as it could be. It was one of the more demanding assignments of my career, simply because the fine balance between the need for personal safety and the need for content is not defined in the same way as it has been for me in other countries.

Many of the rural locations that I visited were unequivocally virginal territory for Western photographers. With a travel ban to North Korea in place for Americans, I felt a responsibility to do a good and accurate job. The access was secured after months of negotiation with the North Korean Embassy in London – I was invited into the country as a guest of the Party.

Good access is often the key to ground-breaking original content and access to most places can normally only be secured through persistence and resourcefulness.

I doubt any western photographer has ever been to this vast steel plant in North Korea before. I was blown away with the visuals. Heavy industry has never looked more visceral and intimidating.
